{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491359"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"921"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/921"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.09,0.05,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106454"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/921"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"430"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43973"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106454"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with an eight-hour history of right eye pain, headache and visual changes. She has vomited once since her symptoms have started.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has hyperopia (long-sightedness), and wears glasses for this. She also uses single-use contacts occasionally, and denies any improper use, including wearing them overnight. She is usually in good health but was recently \u2018under the weather\u2019 with a self-described cold.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is no obvious abnormality to the patient\u2019s left eye, with a visual acuity of 6/6 corrected. Her right eye is red, with a mid-dilated, non-reactive pupil, and the patient struggles to keep the eye open; the visual acuity is 6/36 corrected. No discharge was noted. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis? Choose the single best answer.","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute angle-closure glaucoma","Anterior uveitis","Bacterial keratitis","Ocular Giant Cell Arteritis","Scleritis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERed eye is a common presenting complaint to the emergency department, and it is important to distinguish conditions requiring immediate management. Patient history, visual acuity and ocular examination are important features in determining the cause and management of red eye; these findings provide guidance in the decision to refer for ophthalmological opinion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case stem describes a case of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute angle-closure glaucoma. \u003C/strong\u003ERisk factors for this condition present in the patient include older age (\u0026gt;60 years), female sex, and hyperopia. \u00a0The classical clinical presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute angle closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a red, painful eye with associated nausea and vomiting, a brow headache, blurry vision and haloes around light. Symptoms occur due to increased intra-ocular pressure and associated corneal oedema. On examination, one would expect a fixed, mid-dilated pupil with no or watery discharge. The patient presents with several of these findings \u2013 nausea and vomiting, mid-dilated pupil, and no discharge. Utilisation of a tonometer in the ED setting will allow measurement of an elevated intra-ocular pressure thus making the diagnosis clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial keratitis \u003C/strong\u003Ecauses persistent discharge and photophobia. The largest risk factor for bacterial keratitis\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis improper contact use, which the patient denies. Patients with this condition will often report a foreign body sensation, and struggle to keep the involved eye option. On examination, the diagnostic finding is a corneal opacity or infiltrate (typically a round, white spot) with red eye and mucopurulent discharge. It may or may not affect vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOcular Giant Cell Arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E, would present with loss of vision \u0026lt;6/60 and an relative afferent pupillary defect often associated with a temporal headache and jaw claudication. Giant Cell Arteritis is the most common primary systemic vasculitis typically affecting elderly female patients. This stem has a patient with a vision of 6/36 and a non-reactive pupil, making this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior uveitis\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly associated with immune-mediated disease; however, approximately 30% of patients do not fit into a specific diagnostic category and are instead labelled as having idiopathic uveitis. Examination findings would show a red eye and leukocytes in the anterior chamber of the eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised by severe, constant pain that radiates to the face and periorbital region. It can be associated with headache, watering of the eyes, and ocular redness \u2013 seen in this patient\u2019s case stem. Like anterior uveitis, scleritis is often associated with autoimmune disease. Whilst the patient does present with headache, there is no known autoimmune history, again making this diagnosis less likely.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute angle-closure glaucoma is an ophthalmological emergency, requiring prompt intervention."],"references":["Jacobs DS. The red eye: evaluation and management. In: UpToDate, Gardiner MF (Ed), Wolters Kluwer. Updated July 19, 2022. Accessed March 14, 2024. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/the-red-eye-evaluation-and-management","Gandhewar RR, Kamath GG. Acute glaucoma presentations in the elderly. Emerg Med J. 2005; 22(4)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T23:28:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T23:28:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"921"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106454"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end